  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 장초(萇楚) : '
    value: 《시경》에 있는 노래인데 집없는 것을 탄식한 것이다.
english:
  title: Eleven Self-Addressed Verses
  author: Nam Hyo-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lamplight gathers flame, shadows flicker and sway,
    Disordered snow falls slanting against the window pane.
    My body bears five afflictions already turned to illness—
    Singing of wandering thorns, tears flow like a river.

    When sorrow comes, fever compounds my suffering,
    What can be done? In Chang'an, water grows dear.
    A sick servant holds a bottle by the withered well,
    Each day her twin tears freeze into ice.

    Through Xin and Ren I endured hunger, then came Yi and Si,
    Ten thousand houses scattered—only mine remains.
    Heartbroken by the once-bright southeastern road,
    I see villages upon villages where children are abandoned.

    Yangzi Yun, versed in the Way, composed his Legal Words,
    Yet despised Qu Yuan, wrote his Angry Verses instead.
    Though casting himself from cliffs sought shameful life,
    Who would trade his towering integrity for drowning through ages?

    Tui Zhi strove to become Kongzi,
    Yan Hui, in poverty, held it lightly.
    He submitted his writings—and faced much mockery,
    Yet his name endures in the Four Virtues still.

    Hu Guang's Doctrine of the Mean moved the age,
    As premier of the Six Dynasties, he led ten thousand men.
    Then he laughed at his own starvation on Western Mountain,
    But after death, his flattering fame was soiled for years.

    Xi Kang transcended the world, vanished into darkness,
    Smiling at how common folk are caught in calamity's snare.
    Yet his body too could not escape Zhong Hui's net—
    The Guangling Qin severed; how sorrowful!

    The immortal Cao Tang refined the fire-work of elixirs,
    Once compared to Boyang in vain ambition.
    Lead buried, mercury sunk, the spirit perished at last,
    His tomb's sparse trees dance in the evening wind.

    Shang's nobles and Zhou's culture arose with their ages—
    Three thousand three hundred rites spring from human nature.
    At Fenyin, obscure scholars lack far-reaching vision,
    Outside the rules of conduct, they clumsily fashion their names.

    Liu Xia Hui, sage though hidden in lowly office,
    In his dark cap and easy manner, stood in bright courts.
    Young ones suspect him stained by worldly dust,
    Who knows the Zhou spirit still burns within?

    Zhou Dunyi, Cheng Yi, Zhu Xi, Cai Shen—their Way holds no partiality,
    Where the Luo stream meets the waters of Zi and Si.
    I especially admire Ji Tong, mending the leaking roof—
    At table and desk, writing only verses of solitary practice.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Singing of wandering thorns (張楚): An allusion to a poem in the Book of Odes lamenting homelessness and displacement.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Four Virtues: In Confucian tradition, the four excellences of virtue that define sage-like conduct.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Boyang: An immortal alchemist who sought the elixir of immortality through Taoist practices.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhou spirit: Refers to the spirit of the Zhou dynasty and its ideals of virtue, which the poet believes persists through worthy individuals.'
